postcontent: This is a beautiful example of an original, commercial Model 1906 “American Eagle” Luger that was produced by DWM factory. This series/variation of Luger was manufactured expressly for sale in the United States. The chamber area has the distinctive “American Eagle” crest with the DWM logo on the toggle with the “Crown N” commercial proofs. This model has the correct short style frame and upper receiver with the distinctive “American Eagle” crest over the chamber area with the DWM logo on the toggle, fast taper 4 7/8 inch barrel configuration, grip safety, and polished lower safety area with the correctly marked, “LOADED” extractor. Numbered in the commercial style with full serial number stamped on the underside of the barrel and front of the frame with the last two digits of the serial number stamped on the various small parts. The front end of the frame is stamped “GERMANY” indicating export outside of Europe. It is complete with TWO nickel plated magazine with an unnumbered wooden base.

title: For Sale:  Mak 90+ Extras
postcontent:
I have for sale (as in NO trades, just cash on hand) a NORINCO MAK 90, straight-cut receiver in a "package deal". Priced to sell it all, I'm not parting anything, so what you see is what you get. You can use it, sell it, throw it, hell, I don't care. It's all yours once the sale is final. 
Here is what you get: 
1. The NORINCO Mak 90. Great condition rifle. See pictures. Runs like a champ. If you know AK's, you know the Mak-90 was the closest you could get to military-spec semi-automatic AK awesomeness, until the government banned their importation in '94. It's thicker receiver sets it above the WASR/ MAADI/ etc. crowd you so often see. The double hook trigger is phenomenal. Chrome-lined barrel to resist corrosion better, no matter what ammo you use. See the pictures. Educate yourself on the MAK here-  http://www.mouseguns.com/mak90web/mak90.htm2. Ironwood Furniture- since this is a STRAIGHT cut reciever, you can add additional "show" furniture. I bought it with Ironwood Designs furniture. See their site ironwooddesigns.com3. ORIGINAL MAK-90 furniture with all the trimmings so you can go to the range and shoot it in it's orginal glory. 4. Polish AK magazine pouch kit. Three magazines and a tool with all the eastern european extras in it. Two additional extra mags- one standard, one a hungarian "tanker" magazine. Only 20 rounds, but great for bench- shooting, as it's smaller size gives a much better hold and sight picture when used with a rifle rest. 5. A Kalinka Optics/ Russian rubber butt pad. To help mitigate the recoil, and also to add another inch or so to the pull- extra handy for taller guys. 6. A carrying case. I have no idea who made this, but as you see from the pictures, it neatly holds everything together in a sleek, professional range bag. 
Like I said- priced to sell. They don't bring these things into the US anymore, so it's value has only risen the past few years. After a Hillary election? Hell, you could sell this and make quite a PROFIT after a few months if you were an enterprising flipper. So it can be an investment as much as a great endangered 2nd Amendment piece. I just have other obligations, so I'm parting with mr. Mak.
